newsitem.title: USA: U.S. cash soymeal - Prices too high for end-users.
newsitem.headline: U.S. cash soymeal - Prices too high for end-users.

text.p: Rail and truck soymeal offers in U.S. cash markets were mostly unchanged Friday as end-users continued to wait for lower prices, dealers said.
"I hope the board (CBOT March) goes below $236.00," said one southeastern dealer. "Maybe that would generate some interest in this market."
Most other dealers said activity was quiet.
"We're just kind of limping along here toward at the end of the week," a river dealer said.
The weekly U.S. crushing pace reported by National Oilseed Processors Association was higher than expected.
NOPA reported a crush of 30.335 million bushels. That surpassed the trade range of estimates from 29.3 to 30.0 million bushels.
The crushing pace is expected to remain strong through the middle to end of the month of March, when the soybean crop from Brazil is marketed.
"They (U.S. crushers) had better crush them (soybeans) now, because that South American crop is going to be huge," an Indiana dealer said.
